## What You Need Before Starting
https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/cloud-computing/deploying-a-web-app-on-azure-app-service-step-by-step-guide/
AWS Account (Sign up at: https://aws.amazon.com/)

Putty or Windows Terminal (for SSH into your instance)

A basic app (I'll give you one!)

Internet and browser

## Step-by-Step Guide
## Step 1: Create an EC2 Instance

- Log in to AWS Console

- Go to EC2 → click Launch Instance

- Choose Amazon Linux 2 (Free tier eligible)

- Choose t2.micro (also free tier)

- Create a new key pair (name it e.g., mykey) and download the .pem file

- Leave all defaults, then click Launch

## Step 2: Connect to Your EC2 (from Windows)

- Download PuTTY and PuTTYgen (https://www.putty.org/)

- Use PuTTYgen to convert your .pem file to .ppk

- Load your .pem

- Save the private key as .ppk

- Open PuTTY:

- Host Name: ec2-user@<your-ec2-public-ip>

- Auth → Browse and select your .ppk file

- Click Open → Accept the SSH key warning

## Step 3: Set Up a Web Server
# After you log into the EC2 via PuTTY:

# Update the system
sudo yum update -y

# Install Apache
sudo yum install httpd -y

# Start Apache
sudo systemctl start httpd
sudo systemctl enable httpd

# Allow Apache through firewall
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=http
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

## Step 4: Upload Your Simple Web App
You can upload a simple index.html using WinSCP or FileZilla.
Or, create one directly

## Step 5: Access Your App
# Open your browser

Go to http://<your-ec2-public-ip>

You’ll see your app live!


# Install Python & Flask
- pip3 install flask

Allow Port 5000 in EC2 Security Group
Go back to AWS Console:

Go to EC2 Dashboard

Select your instance → click Security → Security Groups

Click Edit inbound rules

Add a rule:

Type: Custom TCP

Port: 5000


